7B<ue5>10B<ue5>JAN BELL<ql>
<styl>by <m2>By <m0>DALE K. DuPONT<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ql>
<m1><ep>
<m0> Just as the dust was starting to settle, Jan Bell Marketing announced the resignation Monday of the president and chief executive brought in to take the Sunrise jeweler from wholesale to retail.<ep>
  Joseph Pennacchio, 49, was two years into a five-year contract, and the company was in the midst of a turnaround. In releasing results in March, Jan Bell reported its first profitable quarter in nearly three years.<ep>
  But there apparently were some simmering differences about the company's future and how to get more out of its major outlet, Sam's Club.<ep>
  Through aggressive merchandising, Jan Bell wants to increase business at Sam's, where it has 437 leased jewelry departments that account for 91 percent of company sales.<ep>
  ``It may largely be a personality conflict'' between Pennacchio and Isaac Arguetty, Jan Bell's chairman and co-founder, said Ed Tavlin, of Fahnestock & Co. in Hallandale. Tavlin said he didn't think the departure would affect the turnaround.<ep>
  Noting that losses had decreased, Jan Bell spokeswoman Rosemary Trudeau also said the company needed ``to develop strategic plans to explore other opportunities.''<ep>
  Trudeau called Pennacchio's exit an <m1><styl>cxon<ql>
